        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq-a3" id="faq-q3">
            Do I need planning permission for a patio in Ireland?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer" id="faq-a3" role="region" aria-labelledby="faq-q3">
            In most cases, patios in Ireland do not require planning permission as they are considered permitted development, provided they are at ground level and meet standard conditions. However, if your property is in a protected structure zone or you're making significant changes, we'd recommend checking with Tipperary County Council. We can advise you during your free quote.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq-a4" id="faq-q4">
            How much does a patio cost in Tipperary?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer" id="faq-a4" role="region" aria-labelledby="faq-q4">
            Patio costs vary based on size, material, and site preparation requirements. As a general guide, expect entry-level block paving to start from around €60–€90 per m², natural stone from €80–€120 per m², porcelain from €90–€140 per m², and resin bound from €70–€110 per m². These are guidance ranges only — we provide a detailed free quote after assessing your specific site.
